		<article>
			<section>
				<h2>Description</h2>
				<p>
					<span class="nm">kcaldav</span> is a simple CalDav server depending only on <a
						href="http://kristaps.bsd.lv/kcgi">kcgi</a> and <a
						href="http://expat.sourceforge.net/">libexpat</a>.
					It implements the minimal subset of a large number of standards, including <a
						href="https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5545">iCalendar</a>, <a
						href="https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc3744">CalDav</a>, and <a
						href="https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2616">HTTP</a>.
					The ISO C source code is <a href="http://opensource.org/licenses/ISC" rel="license">ISC licensed</a>.
				</p>
				<p>
					To use <span class="nm">kcaldav</span>, you'll need a directory set aside for operation, e.g.,
					<span class="file">/var/www/caldav</span>.
					This should be within a protected <a
						href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi/OpenBSD-current/man2/chroot.2">chroot(2)</a>, for
					which you may need to configure your web server.
					You must then edit the <span class="file">Makefile</span>'s <code>CALDIR</code> to be the path to this
					directory, e.g., <code>/caldav</code>.
					In that directory you'll need a <a href="kcaldav.passwd.5.html">kcaldav.passwd(5)</a> file defining the
					principals (<q>users</q>) of your system.
					For each collection (directory consisting of user calendars) in <span
						class="file">/var/www/caldav</span>, you'll then need a <a
						href="kcaldav.conf.5.html">kcaldav.conf(5)</a> defining the collection and its principals.
					That's it!
				</p>
